### Main Problem (Asan Zaban Mein)
Normal CSS mein agar koi value galat (invalid) ho, to browser turant purani value ignore kar deta hai aur fallback use kar leta hai.

Lekin **Custom Properties (`--var`)** ke saath aisa nahi hota kyunki:

- Pehle **cascade** resolve hota hai (kaunsi value final hai decide hoti hai).
- Uske baad `var()` ko actual value mein convert kiya jata hai.
- Agar final value invalid nikle, to browser purana fallback nahi la sakta – wo already discard ho chuka hota hai.

Isliye error ka naam: **"Invalid at computed-value time"**

### Normal Properties vs Custom Properties (Cascade Behavior)

| Feature                              | Normal CSS Properties                          | Custom Properties (`--var` + `var()`)                  |
|--------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Invalid value hone par               | Turant reject + fallback use                   | Cascade ke baad check → fallback nahi milta          |
| Cascade kab hota hai                 | Value check ke saath                           | Pehle cascade, baad mein variable resolve            |
| Fallback kaam karta hai?             | Haan (`color: red; color: invalid;`)           | Sirf `var(--color, fallback)` mein                     |
| Error type                           | Syntax error (early)                           | Invalid at computed-value time                       |
| Inherited value use hoti hai?        | Depend karta hai property pe                   | Agar invalid ho to inherited ya initial value         |

### Practical Example from Article Concept

```css
:root {
  --text-color: blue;
}

p {
  color: var(--text-color);           /* Normal case → blue */
}

p.error {
  --text-color: 12345;                /* Invalid value (number instead of color) */
  color: red;                         /* Yeh fallback KAAM NAHI karega! */
}
```

**Kya hoga?**  
Paragraph ka color `red` nahi rahega balki inherited value (ya initial black) ho jayega.

### Correct Way – Fallback Use Karo

| Situation                                 | Sahi Tarika                                          | Example |
|-------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|--------|
| Simple fallback                           | `var(--varname, default)`                            | `color: var(--text-color, black);` |
| Nested fallback                           | `var(--a, var(--b, red))`                            | Multiple levels |
| Invalid value avoid karne ke liye         | `@property` use karke type fix karo                  | `syntax: "<color>";` |
| Safe default + inheritance                | `:root` pe default + local override                  | Best practice |

### Key Takeaways & Advice

- Custom properties **dynamic** hain lekin unki validation late hoti hai (computed value time).
- Hamesha `var()` mein **fallback value** dena achha practice hai.
- Agar bohot complex logic hai to **`@property`** at-rule use karo – yeh type safety deta hai aur initial-value bhi set kar sakte ho.
- Cascade samajhna zaroori hai kyunki custom properties normal properties se alag tarike se kaam karte hain.
- Yeh behavior browser mein consistent hai (spec ke mutabiq).

### Quick Tips

1. Har `var()` ke saath fallback zaroor rakho.
2. Private variables (`--_private`) + public variables ka pattern use karo (jaise pehle Kevin Powell video mein bataya tha).
3. Agar color, length, number waghera fix karna hai to `@property` best hai.
4. Testing mein kabhi-kabhi invalid values daal ke dekho ke kya ho raha hai.

